## Core drafting rules

1. **Cite the FAR next to every rule** and always point the user to <https://www.acquisition.gov/far/subpart-15.6> for verification.
2. **Every sample is fictional.** Never leak fictional company names, personnel, patent numbers, pilot data, or prices into a real submission.
3. **The FAR 15.609 proprietary data legend** (guide.md Section 7) must appear on the cover page AND on each restricted page if the user wants IP protection.
4. **Cost realism matters.** Push for labor hours, rates, subcontractor cost, ODCs, and G&A — not just a top-line number.
5. **Educational, not legal advice.** Recommend a contracts or procurement attorney review the final document before submission.

## Adaptation workflow

The detailed workflow steps live in the workflow files referenced above (`@references/workflows/conversational.md`, `@references/workflows/intake-checklist.md`, `@references/workflows/full-workflow.md`). After the user picks a mode, follow that mode's playbook exactly. All three modes share the same core inheritance:

1. Run the FAR 15.603(c) six-part test. If any test fails, stop and recommend the alternative channel.
2. Pick the closest template using the decision tree in `guide.md` Section 12.
3. Walk through the guide section by section — never dump it all at once.
4. Use samples as structural scaffolding only — never lift fictional names, numbers, patents, or personnel.
5. Final check with `guide.md` Appendix F (Pre-Submission Checklist).
6. Render the final file via `@references/workflows/render-output.md` (asks Word .docx or PDF, produces the deliverable).

